{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17616895","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17616895"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:08:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:08:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16444"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16444","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16444"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.44,0.04,0.36,0.12,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9135"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75112"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9135","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9135"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16444"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60620"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1531"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7114"},{"type":"tags","id":"10350"},{"type":"tags","id":"10383"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21700"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21703"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75112","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75112"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EBrain volume naturally decreases with age, but this process affects different regions to varying degrees. Some areas show marked atrophy while others remain relatively preserved throughout the normal ageing process.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following brain regions typically shows the greatest age-related volume loss?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Amygdala","Medulla","Association cortex","Cerebellum","Pons"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ENormal ageing is associated with predictable patterns of brain volume loss. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eassociation cortex\u003C/strong\u003E, particularly in the prefrontal and temporal regions, shows the most prominent age-related atrophy. These areas are involved in higher-order cognitive functions such as executive function, complex decision-making, and memory integration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eamygdala\u003C/strong\u003E shows relatively minimal volume loss in normal ageing, though it may be affected in pathological conditions such as Alzheimer disease. The amygdala is crucial for emotional processing and memory.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emedulla\u003C/strong\u003E, which contains vital centres for autonomic function, typically maintains its volume throughout the ageing process. Significant atrophy here would be pathological rather than age-related.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ecerebellum\u003C/strong\u003E shows some volume loss with ageing but to a lesser extent than the association cortex. The cerebellum is involved in motor coordination and certain cognitive functions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Epons\u003C/strong\u003E, like other brainstem structures, is relatively preserved in normal ageing. It contains important relay nuclei and is involved in sleep, arousal, and other basic functions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding the pattern of normal age-related brain changes is important for distinguishing pathological from physiological processes. While some degree of cortical atrophy is expected with ageing, rapid or asymmetric atrophy may indicate underlying neurodegenerative disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Age-related cortical atrophy predominantly affects the association cortex, particularly in the prefrontal and temporal regions.","Primary sensory and motor cortices are relatively preserved in normal ageing.","Cortical atrophy in ageing is distinct from pathological neurodegenerative processes."],"references":["Schulz M, Mayer C, Schlemm E, Frey BM, Malherbe C, Petersen M, Gallinat J, K\u00fchn S, Fiehler J, Hanning U, Twerenbold R, Gerloff C, Cheng B, Thomalla G. Association of Age and Structural Brain Changes With Functional Connectivity and Executive Function in a Middle-Aged to Older Population-Based Cohort. Front Aging Neurosci. 2022 Feb 25;14:782738. doi: 10.3389/fnagi.2022.782738. PMID: 35283749; PMCID: PMC8916110.","McGinnis SM, Brickhouse M, Pascual B, Dickerson BC. Age-related changes in the thickness of cortical zones in humans. Brain Topogr. 2011 Oct;24(3-4):279-91. doi: 10.1007/s10548-011-0198-6. Epub 2011 Aug 14. PMID: 21842406; PMCID: PMC3600370.","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60620"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16444"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60620","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60620"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-28T22:47:51+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-28T22:48:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9135"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75112"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"6","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/6"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc75","name":"Geriatrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type"